### if-else Statements in C#

The `if-else` statement provides branching logic based on boolean conditions.

### Basic if-else

```csharp
if (condition)
{
    // Runs when condition is true
}
else
{
    // Runs when condition is false
}
```

### Example

```csharp
int temperature = 30;
if (temperature > 25)
{
    Console.WriteLine("It is hot outside");
}
else
{
    Console.WriteLine("It is not too hot");
}
```

### else-if Chain

```csharp
if (score >= 90)
{
    grade = "A";
}
else if (score >= 80)
{
    grade = "B";
}
else if (score >= 70)
{
    grade = "C";
}
else if (score >= 60)
{
    grade = "D";
}
else
{
    grade = "F";
}
```

### Ternary Operator

Shorthand for simple if-else:

```csharp
string result = (score >= 60) ? "Pass" : "Fail";
```

### Common Pitfalls

| Mistake | Wrong | Correct |
|---------|-------|---------|
| Assignment in condition | `if (x = 5)` | `if (x == 5)` |
| Missing braces | `if (true) x = 5; y = 10;` | `if (true) { x = 5; y = 10; }` |
| Semicolon after if | `if (condition); { ... }` | `if (condition) { ... }` |

### Short-Circuit Evaluation

```csharp
// Second condition is NOT evaluated if first is false
if (obj != null && obj.Count > 0)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Has items");
}
```

> **Key Point:** Always use braces `{}` even for single statements to avoid bugs. Only the first matching condition executes in an if-else chain - the rest are skipped.

### Pattern Matching with if (C# 7+)

```csharp
if (shape is Circle c)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Circle radius: {c.Radius}");
}
else if (shape is Rectangle r && r.Width > 0)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Rectangle area: {r.Width * r.Height}");
}
```

codeExample:
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        Console.Write("Enter your score: ");
        int score = int.Parse(Console.ReadLine());

        string grade;

        if (score >= 90)
            grade = "A";
        else if (score >= 80)
            grade = "B";
        else if (score >= 70)
            grade = "C";
        else if (score >= 60)
            grade = "D";
        else
            grade = "F";

        Console.WriteLine($"Your grade: {grade}");
        Console.WriteLine(grade == "F" ? "Better luck next time" : "Good job!");
    }
}
